    {
      "question_number": 13,
      "question_text": "Higher discount rates make future cash flows worth _____ today.",
      "attempted": 2,
      "data_i18n": null,
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "More — higher rates mean money grows faster",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "The same — present value doesn't depend on the discount rate",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Less (future money is 'discounted' more heavily when alternative returns are higher)",
          "is_correct": true,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "It depends entirely on inflation, not the discount rate",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        }
      ],
      "explanation": "Present value and discount rate have an inverse relationship: PV = FV / (1 + r)^n. A higher r means dividing by a larger number, reducing the present value. Intuitively, if you can earn 10% elsewhere, a future $1,000 is worth less to you today than if you could only earn 3% — you need less money today to reach the same future amount."
    },
